\par }\pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {Before You Begin...}{\b 
\par }{Remember that }{\i passwords are case-sensitive, }{and}{\i  }{note whether your keyboard has Caps Lock on.}{\b  }{Leash32 is}{\b  }{not programmed to inform you about the state of your Caps Lock key.
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {\b How To Use Change Password...}{
\par }\pard \fi-600\li720\widctlpar\adjustright {\b 1.}{\tab In Leash32, click on the Modify Password button (the one that says abc and has a green arrow), type your username in the first field of the dialogue box t
hat opens, and press Enter or click OK. You may start over anytime by clicking Restart, stop at any time by clicking Cancel, or get help at any time with the Help button.
\par }{\b 2.}{\tab Type your }{\i current}{ password in the second field and press Enter or click OK.
\par }\pard \li720\widctlpar\adjustright {The program checks the username and password you entered and notifies you if either is invalid.
\par }\pard \fi-600\li720\widctlpar\adjustright {\b 3.}{\tab Type your }{\i new}{ password in the third field and press Enter or click OK.
\par }{\b 4}{.\tab Retype your }{\i new}{ password, to verify it, and press Enter or click OK.
\par }\pard \li720\widctlpar\adjustright {Once you have entered the new password twice with consistent spellings, the Leash32 program replaces your old password with the new, }{\i if it is a strong password. }{
If Kerberos determines the password is weak, a message notifies you, and you need to}{\i  }{repeat steps 1 through 4 with a strong password, as described by the "How To Choose a Password" guidelines above.
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {
\par }\pard\plain \s16\li120\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\b\f0 How Change Password Works...}{
\par }\pard\plain \s19\li115\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {When you type into the password fields of the dialog box, neither characters nor sounds echo back, thus keeping secret even the number of pass
word characters. The program accepts only printable characters for new passwords, i.e., characters between ASCII codes 0x20 and 0x7E.
\par }\pard\plain \li115\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {
\par }\pard \li90\widctlpar\adjustright {When you have entered the new password twice consistently, the program attempts to change the password via a dialogue wit
h the Kerberos administrative server. Some Kerberos sites, including MIT's Athena environment, check the password's strength before allowing the change to take place and notifies you if it determines that the password is weak.}{\fs18 
