\par }\pard\plain \s21\widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {See Also
\par }\pard\plain \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {\uldb Kerberos tickets}{\v ID_HELP_TICKETS}{\uldb 
\par AFS tokens}{
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {\page   }{\cs15\super ${\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super $}{ Leash Properties Command}}}{ }{\cs15\super #{\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain 
\s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super #}{ HID_LEASH_PROPERTIES_COMMAND}}}{\b\fs24 Leash32 Properties Command
\par }{
\par Here, in the Edit menu, you can change the location of Leash32\rquote s configuration file, and select a time server from which 
Leash32 will obtain the correct time.  The time is needed by Leash32 because of the time dependencies in Kerberos. When you specify a server here, it will try to get the time from that server when you next run the Synchronize Time command. If it fails, it
 will tell you this, and revert to the server \ldblquote time\rdblquote ; no matter what Leash32 does, it will tell you where it found the time. See the Synchronize Time command for more information on this.
\par }\pard \fi720\widctlpar\adjustright {
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {\page   }{\cs15\super ${\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super $}{ Kerberos Properties Command}}#{\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain 
\s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super #}{ HID_KERBEROS_PROPERTIES_COMMAND}}}{\b\fs24 Kerberos Properties Command
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {
\par When you select this from the Edit menu, Leash32 will bring up a window. The box within this window has three tabs: Client Configuration Options, Realm/Host Maintenance, and Domain-Host/Realm Maintenance.
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {\b Client Configuration Options:
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {
\par }\pard \li720\widctlpar\adjustright {
There are two boxes here, the Kerberos Realm/Host Server box and the Computer Host/Domain Name box. In the Kerberos Realm/Host Server area, you can select a Kerberos realm from the list given in Realm/Host Maintenance. Once you do this, Leash32 
will automatically fill in your Kerberos server with the first server in the list under Realm/Host Maintenance. 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {
\par }\pard \li720\widctlpar\adjustright {Computer Host/Domain Name: Under Your Computer\rquote s Host Name, you want to enter its DNS host name; the DNS domain name goes under Your Computer\rquote 
s Domain Name.  These can be found in the TCP/IP control panel, accessed by selecting Settings->Control Panel from your computer\rquote s Start menu, in the very bottom left corner of the screen.
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {
\par }\pard \fi720\widctlpar\adjustright {\i Realm/Host Maintenance}{:
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {
\par }\pard \li1440\widctlpar\adjustright {Here, you have two choices: Kerberos Real
ms, and Servers Hosting a KDC. To add a new realm, click on the Insert box underneath the existing realms. You can then type in the name of your realm. However, for the realm to exist, it needs one or more servers. Immediately after you enter the new real
m name, you will be prompted for the names of servers in that realm. If you do not enter at least one server, Kerberos will not recognize the realm.
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {
\par }\pard \li1440\widctlpar\adjustright {To add servers to an existing realm, click on that realm, then choose Insert under Servers Hosting a KDC. Y
ou will be prompted for the name of the new server. You can also remove servers, and designate either one or none as the administrative server. By clicking and dragging on the server which you want to move, you can change their order; this is important be
cause the server listed at the top appears in Client Configuration Options under Your Kerberos Server.
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {
\par }\pard \fi720\widctlpar\adjustright {\i Domain Host/Realm Maintenance}{: 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {
\par }\pard \li1440\widctlpar\adjustright {Each entry
 here consists of two portions: the DNS domain name (such as .mit.edu) followed by the Kerberos realm (such as ATHENA.MIT.EDU). You can add entries in his form; here, you can also edit existing ones, or delete old entries.
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {\page   }{\cs15\super ${\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super $}{ Kerberos Four Properties Command}}#{\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain 
\s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super #}{ HID_KRB4_PROPERTIES_COMMAND}}}{\b\fs24 Kerberos Four Properties command}{
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {
\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {This command is accessible from the Edit menu. Here, you can specify the location where you wish your Kerberos tickets to be stored \endash  for instance, whether you want them on disk (and i
f so, where), or in a memory cache. Additionally, you can supply the path of the configuration file. In addition to specifying this yourself, Leash32 also gives you the option of finding these paths with krb.con or krbrealm.con.\page   }{\cs15\super $
{\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super $}{ Kerberos Five Properties Command}}#{\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super #}
{ HID_KRB5_PROPERTIES_COMMAND}}}{\b\fs24 Kerberos Five Properties Command}{
\par }\pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {
\par }\pard\plain \s27\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {There are two options found here (here being from the Edit menu): File Location and Configuration Options. 
\par }\pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {
\par The File Location tab allows you to specify the location of the configuration file and the tickets, which can be stored in any location on disk or in the memory cache.
\par 
\par In the Configuration Options section, you can say whether or not you want the Kerberos 5 tickets obtained by Leash32 to be forwardable. Forwarding is an optio
n only available with Kerberos 5. With this box checked, when you telnet or otherwise transfer to another machine, your tickets will be forwarded there. Therefore, you will not have to reauthenticate yourself. Otherwise, when you connect to the new machin
e, you will have to obtain new tickets.
\par \page   }{\cs15\super ${\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super $}{ AFS Properties Command}}#{\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {
\cs15\super #}{ HID_AFS_PROPERTIES_COMMAND}}}{\b\fs24 AFS Properties Command
\par }{
\par This choice, found on the Edit menu, will cause Leash32 to bring up a window. Here, there are three available tab: Client Properties, Cell Hosts, and Submounts.
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {\b Client Properties:
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {
\par }\pard \li720\widctlpar\adjustright {Here, you can specify your AFS cell name (if you are using Leash32 at MIT, this is likely athena.mit.edu unless you know differently.) You can also change the cache size and the page size from AFS default val
ues. You also can change what kind of system AFS thinks you are running, specify whether you want logon authentication, whether you want AFS to be able to handle long and short names or short names only, and set the cell probe interval from the default of
 30 seconds.
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {\tab 
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {\b Cell Hosts:
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {
\par }\pard \li720\widctlpar\adjustright {This lists all possible AFS hosts. You can add one to the list if you know its cell name, the names of the servers, and the IP address.  You can also delete cells, or change information for preexisting ones.
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {\page   }{\cs15\super ${\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super $}{ Debug Window Option}}#{\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain 
\s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super #}{ HID_DEBUG_WINDOW_OPTION}}}{\b\fs24 Debug Window Option
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {
\par When this option (found under the View menu) is checked, the Leash32 Debug Window appears. From this window, commands that Leash32 issues to the Kerberos server are visible. Here, you can
 see exactly what Leash32 is doing. This option is useful if you are having a problem with Leash32 and want to see more exactly what is going on, or if you are writing Kerberized applications dependent on Kerberos tickets or the actions of Leash32.
\par \page   }{\cs15\super ${\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super $}{ Large Icons Option}}#{\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {
\cs15\super #}{ HID_LARGE_ICONS_OPTION}}}{\b\fs24 Large Icons Option
\par }\pard\plain \s21\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {
\par }\pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {When this option, found on the View menu, is checked, the icons in the main window (such as the cute little picture of Kerberos) will be much larger. The default setting of Leash32 has this op
tion selected. \page   }{\cs15\super ${\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super $}{ Toolbar Option}}#{\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright 
\f5\fs20 {\cs15\super #}{ HID_TOOLBAR_OPTION}}}{\b\fs24 Toolbar Option}{
\par 
\par By default, this option on the View menu is selected. When it is checked, the toolbar containing icons for commonly used commands is visible. Otherwise, Leash32 hides it.\page   }{\cs15\super ${\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0
\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super $}{ Status Bar Option}}#{\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super #}{ HID_STATUS_BAR_OPTION}}}{\b\fs24 Status Bar Option}{
\par }\pard\plain \s21\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {
\par }\pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {This is also on by default; turning it off will cause the bar at the bottom of the Leash32 window with the time remaining on any tickets which you might have to disappear.\page   }{\cs15\super $
{\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super $}{\b\fs24  }{Destroy Tickets/Tokens on Exit Option }}#{\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright 
\f5\fs20 {\cs15\super #}{ HID_DESTROY_TICKETS_ON_EXIT}}}{\b\fs24 Destroy Tickets/Tokens on Exit Option}{
\par 
\par If this option is selected under the Options menu, Leash32 destroys your tickets and tokens when you shut it down; otherwise, the tickets remain. This option is turned off by default. \page   }{\cs15\super ${\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain 
\s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super $}{ Upper Case Realm Name Option}}#{\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super #}{ HID_UPPERCASE_REALM_OPTION}}}{
\b\fs24 Upper Case Realm Name Option}{
\par 
\par Default for this (accessible from the Options menu) is off; when it is selected, the Kerberos realm name that you type (such as ATHENA.MIT.EDU) will be converted to upper case regardless of how you type it.
\par \page 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {  }{\cs15\super ${\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super $}{ Low Ticket/Token Time Alarm Option}}#{\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain 
\s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super #}{ HID_LOW_TICKET_ALARM_OPTION}}}{\b\fs24 Low Ticket/Token Time Alarm Option}{
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {
\par Leash32 will always pop up windows with warnings that your tickets are about to expire, beginning 15 minutes before the time of expiration and continuing every 5 minutes. However, when this option is selected under the Options menu, a bell will ring as we
l
l. When you view your tickets and tokens, those shown in yellow are due to expire in less than 15 minutes; those in green have 15 minutes or greater. (A red, torn ticket is one which you can have but currently do not; gray tickets are not available to you
 at the current time, because Leash32 is missing a requisite module or piece of functionality.)
\par \page 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {  }{\cs15\super ${\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super $}{ Synchronize Time Option}}#{\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain 
\s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super #}{ HID_SCNCHRONIZE_TIME_OPTION}}}{\b\fs24 Synchronize Time Option}{
\par }\pard\plain \s21\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {
\par }\pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {When you select this option under the Options menu, Leash32 will synchroni
ze its time with the time server selected in Leash32 Properties, under the Edit menu. Because of the time dependence of Kerberos tickets, these need to be within 4 minutes of each other for Kerberos to function properly. This function can also be performe
d with the clock icon on the toolbar.
\par  \page   }{\cs15\super ${\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super $}{ Reset Window Size/Pos Option}}#{\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright 
\f5\fs20 {\cs15\super #}{ HID_RESET_WINDOW_OPTION}}}{\b\fs24 Reset Window Size/Pos Option}{
\par 
\par When you select this from the Options menu, the Leash32 window moves to its original size and position, near the upper left corner of the screen. \page   }{\cs15\super ${\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright 
\f5\fs20 {\cs15\super $}{ Krbcheck Option}}#{\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super #}{ HID_KRBCHECK_OPTION}}}{\b\fs24 Krbcheck Option}{
\par 
\par Found under the Options menu, this runs the krbcheck application. Krbcheck goes through your Kerberos setup and detects if there are any problems. If there are, it tells you 
about them, and offers help in solving them. Additionally, from within krbcheck Leash32 will tell you many pieces of information, such as the DNS name of your computer, whether many different files and options are available, about the ldap server, and muc
h much more I don\rquote t understand.
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {\page   Leash32 Command
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {\tab \tab 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {This command found under the Help menu starts Leash32 help (the document you are currently in }{\lang1024 {\field{\*\fldinst SYMBOL 74 \\f "Wingdings" \\s 10}{\fldrslt\f14\fs20}}}{ ) 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {
\par }\pard\plain \s17\widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\f0\cgrid \page   Kerberos Command
\par }\pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {
\par This command, located in the Help menu, provides the Kerberos section of the Leash32 help document.
\par \page }{\cs15\super ${\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {\cs15\super $}{ About Leash32 Command}}#{\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super #}{
 HID_ABOUT_LEASH32_COMAND}}}{\b\fs24 About Leash32 Command}{
\par 
\par When you access this from the Help menu, you will be given three choices: Leash32 Modules, Missing Modules, and All Modules. 
\par 
\par Leash32 Modules tells you the modules (executables and the .dll application files which they require) which Leash32 currently has loaded for its own use; All Modules includes those loaded by NT as well. Missi
ng Modules will say modules needed for Leash32 for complete functionality of all portions that aren\rquote t there. (Leash32 can still function with some of these missing\'85
) This is useful if part of Leash32 is missing; you can find which files are needed to restore full functionality. 
\par 
\par Additionally, if you hit the Properties button, Leash32 will give you the properties of the selected  module \endash  both the general properties and those of this particular version.
\par 
\par \page    kdestroy.exe program
\par 
\par This is another way to destroy your tickets. Running this application will immediately destroy all tickets and tokens you might have, no matter how they were obtained.
\par \page   kinit.exe\tab program
\par 
\par This is a little program which will run a command-prompt, text-based version of the ticket in
itialization window. (However, unlike in the graphical version, you do not have the option of changing the ticket lifetime.) This can be useful if you have a slow computer, or if you are having difficulty with the graphical version for some reason.\page 
  klist.exe program
\par \tab 
\par This application will quickly list all of the tickets you have and then disappear. I fail to see why this is useful at the moment unless you have very fast eyes. Perhaps I will soon.
