\par }\pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {
\par A Kerberos name contains three parts. The 
first is the principal name, which is usually a user's or service's name. The second is the instance, which in the case of a user is usually null. Some users may have privileged instances, however, such as ``root'' or ``admin''. In the case of a service, 
the instance is the name of the machine on which it runs; i.e. there can be an }{\b rlogin}{
 service running on the machine ABC, which is different from the rlogin service running on the machine XYZ. The third part of a Kerberos name is the realm. The realm corres
ponds to the Kerberos service providing authentication for the principal. For example, at MIT there is a Kerberos running at the Laboratory for Computer Science and one running at Project Athena.
\par 
\par When writing a Kerberos name, the principal name is separated from the instance (if not null) by a period, and the realm (if not the local realm) follows, preceded by an ``@'' sign. The following are examples of valid Kerberos names:
\par }\pard \li2160\widctlpar\adjustright {billb
\par jis.admin
\par srz@LCS.MIT.EDU
\par treese.root@ATHENA.MIT.EDU
\par }\pard\plain \s1\li120\sb280\sa120\sl-320\slmult0\nowidctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright \b\f5 {\page }{\cs15\super ${\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super $}{ Leash Screen Displ
ay (Kerberometer and Dash Notification)}}}{ }{\cs15\super #{\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super #}{ ID_HELP_METER}}}{ Leash32 Screen Display (Kerberometer and Dash Notification)
\par }\pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {
\par \tab The top of the window will have the name of the application (Leash32 }{\lang1024 {\field{\*\fldinst SYMBOL 74 \\f "Wingdings" \\s 10}{\fldrslt\f14\fs20}}}{ ) and the date and time.
\par Below that will be a menu bar and a toolbar, followed by the main Leash32 window. The window has scroll bars, so that you can view all of your tickets. If all of this information fits into the window in its current size, the scroll bars will disappear.

\par 
\par }\pard \fi720\widctlpar\adjustright {Fo
r each set of Kerberos tickets, the main Leash32 program screen displays information about their current status, including the time that they were issued and the time that they will expire. Click on the large plus sign in front of the tickets to expand th
e
 tree, giving more information; clicking on the minus sign retracts the tree . If you want an update of your ticket status (if, for instance, you destroyed your tickets and want to see that reflected, or want to see your new tickets), you can either click
 in the window or use the Update Display command found on the toolbar. Otherwise, the display will automatically update itself every 30 seconds.
\par 
\par At the bottom right, directly above the Leash32 icon, the }{\b Kerberometer}{ displays your tickets' remaining time (both Kerberos 4/AFS and Kerberos 5 \endash 
 as some programs obtain only Kerberos 4 tickets, these are not necessarily the same) in hours, minutes, and seconds. 
\par \tab 
\par Each ticket is described and represented with an icon of a little ticket. The color of the ticket changes based on its viability: 
\par }\pard \li2160\widctlpar\adjustright {green = normal
\par yellow = tickets are within 15 minutes of expiration
\par red, torn = tickets have expired, or you have no tickets
\par gray = these tickets are not available to you
\par }\pard \fi720\widctlpar\adjustright {At 15, 10, and 5 minutes before your Kerberos tickets expire, you receive}{\b  dash-style notification}{
 -- a screen pops up to warn that your Kerberos tickets will expire soon and to give you the opportunity to renew them.
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {
