\par }\pard\plain \s1\li120\sb280\sa120\sl-320\slmult0\nowidctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright \b\f5 {\page }{\cs15\super ${\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super $}{
 Kerberos:  How does the other guy know who I am?}}}{ }{\cs15\super #{\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super #}{ ID_HELP_SIPB}}}{ Kerberos: How Does the Other Guy Know Who I Am?
\par }\pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {
\par A portion of the text below was copied with permission from }{\i An Inessential Guide to Athena}{ (5th edition) published by the Student Information Processing Board.
\par }\pard \qc\widctlpar\adjustright {
\par }\pard\plain \s17\sb120\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {Athena has developed a system known as Kerberos to provide for sec
urity on a physically insecure network. A complete description of the mechanisms used by Kerberos to provide this security is beyond the scope of this document. This section describes why Kerberos is necessary in the Athena environment, the theory behind 
Kerberos (with pointers to further information), and the user commands which interface to Kerberos. It also gives hints for using Kerberos more effectively.
\par }\pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {
\par }\pard\plain \s17\sb120\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\b Why}{ }{\b Kerberos}{ }{\b is }{\cs15\super #{\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super #}{ ID_HELP_AUTHENTIC}}}{\fs18\up6  }{\b 
needed}{. Most moderately-sized to large computer systems use some form of password protection scheme to }{\i authenticate }{
users; that is, they require a user who wishes to log in to give both his name and a secret password which only he and the computer system know. Anyone who happens to know the password can claim to be 
that user. It is therefore desirable to prevent people from listening in on the conversation between the computer and the user's terminal or workstation.
\par }\pard\plain \s21\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {
\par }\pard\plain \s17\sb120\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {This is relatively easy in the case of terminals directly connected to the machine, since each termin
al has its own cable. In a local-area network, several (typically between 10 and 200) computers share one cable, and any computer can listen in on any network traffic. With the advent of network monitoring packages for IBM PC's and similar machines, it is
 
relatively easy for a determined user to set up a program to listen in on a network for any and all passwords being sent over. This would allow an intruder to masquerade as someone else, violating their privacy and perhaps stealing information (academic o
r otherwise). }{\b Note that THE ELECTRONIC COMMUNICATIONS PRIVACY ACT of 1986 makes this a Federal crime}{ punishable by lots of nasty stuff (ask your lawyer for details).
\par }\pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {
\par }\pard\plain \s17\sb120\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {In addition, since Athena uses a workstation-based model of computation, wi
th most operations taking place on a single-user workstation with occasional requests (for files, etc.) going to other "server" machines, Athena needed to set up some way to allow users to }{\i prove}{ their identity to such server machines.
\par 
\par }{\b A few definitions}{. Knowledge of the following terms is not essential for use of Kerberos but is helpful in understanding what is going on:
\par }\pard \s17\fi-1440\li1440\sb120\nowidctlpar\adjustright {\b user:}{\tab A human being who wishes to use a computer system. A user, through his workstation, may make a series of requests to several server
s in the course of a session, and would like to avoid (due to sheer laziness, among other things) having to type his password to each machine in question.
\par }{\b service:}{\tab A program or set of programs running on a computer which is accessible over the network. The service would like to know with certainty that the workstation to which it is providing the service is really being used by the }{\b user}{
 who claims to be logged in on the workstation. Note that workstations are }{\i not }{services, and thus one may not use Kerberos to log into them over the network.
\par }{\cs15\super #{\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super #}{ ID_HELP_PRINCIPAL}}}{\fs18\up6  }{\b principal:}{\tab 
An entity which can both prove its identity and verify the identities of other principals who wish to communicate with it; each }{\b user}{ and each }{\b service}{ registered with Kerberos is thus a principal.
\par }{\b ticket:}{ \tab 
A block of data which, when given to a user, enables him to prove his identity to a service. In the Athena environment tickets are stored in files in the /tmp directory, and are automatically erased on log-out. On DOS and Windows tickets a
re stored in RAM in an area of memory reserved by the program Kerbmem. They are automatically erased when the computer is rebooted or when the user issues the destroy tickets command from Leash32. They may also be destroyed from DOS by typing kdestroy. Th
e
y contain information which must be considered private to the user, and thus the file should be kept at protection mode 700. As they contain a time stamp, they cease to be valid after eight hours. One ticket is needed for each service; tickets are used to
 build }{\b authenticators}{, which are sent over the network to the service.
\par }{\b authenticator:}{ \tab A block of data which a user's workstation sends over the network to a specific service to prove that the workstation really is in use by that user. An authenticator expi
res after five minutes. One authenticator is typically built per session of use of a service; once the service decodes the authenticator, it generally permits the user to operate for as long as she wants. This behavior is not in any way mandated by the Ke
rberos suite of programs and libraries (it is just a detail of the implementation), but it is convenient and considered secure enough for the Athena environment.
\par }\pard \s17\sb120\nowidctlpar\adjustright {
\par }\pard \s17\sb120\nowidctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {\b How It Works...
\par }\pard \s17\sb120\nowidctlpar\adjustright {Kerberos uses a standard encryption-based authentication technique with a few 
variations designed to increase ease of use across administrative entities and reduce the number of possible "attacks" on the system. The system uses cryptographically sealed }{\i tickets}{ and }{\i authenticators}{\}
 which may be passed over the network and decrypted only by a user or machine which knows the appropriate encryption/decryption key.
\par 
\par }\pard \s17\sb120\nowidctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {\b Using Kerberos...}{
\par }\pard \s17\sb120\nowidctlpar\adjustright {Most of the programs in use with Kerberos are located in the standard user path. Some of the programs in
stalled in the standard locations for 4.3BSD are actually versions of the programs converted to use Kerberos, so that most of your interaction with Kerberos will be "under the covers'" and should not look or act any different than standard 4.3BSD.
\par 
\par }\pard \s17\sb120\nowidctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {\b Registering with Kerberos...
\par }\pard \s17\sb120\nowidctlpar\adjustright {
If you have an account registered with Athena, you are registered with Kerberos. If you do not have an Athena account, talk to the Athena Accounts Administrator at x3-1325 to either set up an Athena account or register with Kerberos.
\par 
\par Once registered with Kerberos, tickets are obtained by the login program every time you log onto a workstation. You can also manually obtain new tickets (which you usually do only if your old ones have expired, 10 hours after you log in) by running the pr
ogram}{\f2  kinit}{. It prompts for a username, requests an initial ticket from Kerberos, and then asks for your password. If you are not registered with Kerberos, it will print}{\f2  Principal unknown (Kerberos)}{
. Unless you mistype your username, this should not happen. To correct this, or any other errors, contact a Consultant or the Athena Accounts Administrator.
\par }\pard\plain \s1\li120\sb280\sa120\sl-320\slmult0\nowidctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright \b\f5 {\b0\fs18\up6 
\par }{\page }{\cs15\super ${\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super $}{ How Kerberos Shares Tickets}}}{ }{\cs15\super #{\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0
\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super #}{ ID_HELP_SHARE_TICKETS}}}{ How Kerberos Shares Tickets
\par }\pard\plain \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {\b Why Do It...}{
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {In the Athena environment Kerberos tickets are stored ei
ther on the local disk drive or in the workstation's memory. Tickets are obtained when the user logs into the Athena environment. Thus, during normal operation, users enter a password once only. On some other platforms, however, the tickets are stored sep
arately in each Kerberized application, and each time one of these Kerberized applications starts, the user must re-enter the password.
\par When the developers at Brown University began porting the Kerberos libraries to DOS and Windows, they elected to create a system that enables all applications to share Kerberos tickets. With this system }{\i the user enters a password once only}{
 for an entire suite of Kerberized applications. Thus, they created the program Kerbmem, whose first task is reserving memory for the ticket storage before trying to obtain tickets and before loading Windows.
\par (The Brown developers' second reason for developing Kerbmem is that they wanted to store Kerberos tickets in shared RAM memory on the PC; they wanted to avoid storing the tickets on the local disk since PCs are inherently insecure.)
\par }\pard\plain \s16\li120\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\b 
\par }\pard \s16\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {\b How It's Done...}{
\par }\pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {The Kerbmem program comes with MIT's Network Services LAN WorkPlace distribution. Members of the MIT community may obtain a copy of LAN WorkPlace at no charge from the Network Help Desk. Please call 3-4101.

\par Running MIT's LAN WorkPlace installation program automatically installs Kerbmem as well as other network software. Kerbmem is copied to the \\net\\kerb directory, which also 
contains the Kerberos configuration files and some DOS command line utilities for working with Kerberos tickets.
\par By default Kerbmem reserves 1 Kb of RAM for storing tickets. If you need more room to store tickets, you may pass Kerbmem a command line option to reserve more room.
\par If you need to remove Kerbmem from memory, first make sure that there are no TSR programs loaded above it. Then unload it by typing "kerbmem -u". It will tell you whether the unload is successful.
\par Kerbmem also sets an environment var
iable named KERBEROS_TICKETS. Users should not modify this variable! It is used by the Kerberos libraries and DLL to locate the storage space reserved for the tickets. Any modifications to the variable can make the system unstable--in the }{\i best}{
 case you will not be able to recover the reserved memory until you reboot your machine.
\par The program Kerbmem is copyrighted (c) 1993 by Brown University.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s1\li120\sb280\sa120\sl-320\slmult0\nowidctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright \b\f5 {\page }{\cs15\super ${\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super $}{ KINIT Command}}}{ }{
\cs15\super #{\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super #}{ ID_HELP_KINIT}}}{ KINIT Command
\par }\pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {
\par (from UNIX man page)
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {NAME
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {     kinit - obtain and cache Kerberos ticket-granting ticket
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {SYNOPSIS
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {     kinit
\par           [-l lifetime] [-s start_time] [-v] [-p] [-f] [-k [-t
\par           keytab_file]] [-r renewable_life] [-R] [-c cache_name]
\par           [-S service_name] [principal]
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {DESCRIPTION
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {     kinit obtains and caches an initial  ticket-granting  ticket
\par      for principal.
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {OPTIONS
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {     -l lifetime
\par           requests a ticket  with  the  lifetime  lifetime.   The
\par           value  for lifetime must be followed immediately by one
\par           of the following delimiters:
\par 
\par              s  seconds
\par             m  minutes
\par              h  hours
\par              d  days
\par 
\par           as in "kinit -l 90m".  You cannot mix units; a value of
\par           `3h30m' will result in an error.
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {          If the -l option is not specified, the  default  ticket
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {          lifetime (configured by each site) is used.  Specifying
\par           a ticket lifetime longer than the maximum ticket  life-
\par           time (configured by each site) results in a ticket with
\par           the maximum lifetime.
\par 
\par      -s start_time
\par           requests  a  postdated  ticket,   valid   starting   at
\par           start_time.   Postdated  tickets  are  issued  with the
\par           invalid flag set, and need to be fed back  to  the  kdc
\par           before use.
\par 
\par      -v   requests that the ticket granting ticket in  the  cache
\par           (with  the  invalid  flag set) be passed to the kdc for
\par           validation.  If the ticket is within its requested time
\par           range, the cache is replaced with the validated ticket.
\par 
\par      -p   request proxiable tickets.
\par 
\par      -f   request forwardable tickets.
\par 
\par      -r renewable_life
\par           requests renewable tickets, with a  total  lifetime  of
\par           renewable_life.   The duration is in the same format as
\par           the -l option, with the same delimiters.
\par 
\par      -R   requests renewal of the ticket-granting  ticket.   Note
\par           that  an  expired ticket cannot be renewed, even if the
\par           ticket is still within its renewable life.
\par 
\par      -k [-t keytab_file]
\par           requests a host ticket, obtained  from  a  key  in  the
\par           local host's keytab file.  The name and location of the
\par           keytab file may be specified with  the  -t  keytab_file
\par           option; otherwise the default name and location will be
\par           used.
\par 
\par      -c cache_name
\par           use cache_name as the credentials (ticket)  cache  name
\par           and  location;  if this option is not used, the default
\par           cache name and location are used.
\par 
\par           The default credentials cache may vary between systems.
\par           If  the  KRB5CCNAME  environment  variable  is set, its
\par           value is used to name the default  ticket  cache.   Any
\par           existing contents of the cache are destroyed by kinit.
\par 
\par      -S service_name
\par           specify an alternate service name to use  when  getting
\par           initial tickets.
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {ENVIRONMENT
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {     Kinit uses the following environment variable:
\par 
\par      KRB5CCNAME      Location of the credentials (ticket) cache.
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {FILES
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {     /tmp/krb5cc_[uid]  default credentials cache ([uid]  is  the
\par                         decimal UID of the user).
\par 
\par      /etc/krb5.keytab   default location  for  the  local  host's
\par                         keytab file.
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {SEE ALSO
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {     klist(1), kdestroy(1), krb5(3)
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s1\li120\sb280\sa120\sl-320\slmult0\nowidctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright \b\f5 {\page }{\cs15\super ${\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super $}{ KLIST Command}}}{ }{
\cs15\super #{\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super #}{ ID_HELP_KLIST}}}{ KLIST Command
\par }\pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {
\par (from UNIX man page)
\par 
\par User Commands                                            KLIST(1)
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {NAME
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {     klist - list cached Kerberos tickets
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {SYNOPSIS
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {     klist [-e] [[-c]  [-f]  [-s]  [cache_name]]  [-k  [-t]  [-K]
\par      [keytab_name]]
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {DESCRIPTION
\par      Klist lists the Kerberos principal and Kerberos tickets held
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {     in a credentials cache, or the keys held in a keytab file.
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {OPTIONS
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {     -e   displays the encryption types of the  session  key  and
\par           the ticket for each credential in the credential cache,
\par           or each key in the keytab file.
\par 
\par      -c   List tickets held in a credentials cache.  This is  the
\par           default if neither -c nor -k is specified.
\par 
\par      -f   shows the flags present in the credentials,  using  the
\par           following abbreviations:
\par 
\par                F    Forwardable
\par                f    forwarded
\par                P    Proxiable
\par                p    proxy
\par                D    postDateable
\par                d    postdated
\par                R    Renewable
\par                I    Initial
\par                i    invalid
\par 
\par      -s   causes klist to run silently (produce no  output),  but
\par           to  still  set  the exit status according to whether it
\par           finds the credentials cache.  The exit status is `0' if
\par           klist  finds  a  credentials  cache, and `1' if it does
\par           not.
\par 
\par      -k   List keys held in a keytab file.
\par 
\par      -t   display the time entry timestamps for each keytab entry
\par            in the keytab file.
\par 
\par      -K   display the value of the encryption key in each  keytab
\par           entry in the keytab file.
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {     If cache_name or keytab_name is not  specified,  klist  will
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {     display  the credentials in the default credentials cache or
\par      keytab file as appropriate.  If the  KRB5CCNAME  environment
\par      variable  is  set,  its  value  is  used to name the default
\par      ticket cache.
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {ENVIRONMENT
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {     Klist uses the following environment variable:
\par 
\par      KRB5CCNAME      Location of the credentials (ticket) cache.
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {FILES
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {     /tmp/krb5cc_[uid]  default location of the credentials cache
\par      ([uid] is the decimal UID of the user).
\par 
\par      /etc/krb5.keytab   default location of the keytab file.
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {SEE ALSO
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {     kinit(1), kdestroy(1), krb5(3)
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s1\li120\sb280\sa120\sl-320\slmult0\nowidctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright \b\f5 {\page }{\cs15\super ${\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super $}{ KDESTROY Command}}}{ }{
\cs15\super #{\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super #}{ ID_HELP_KDESTROY}}}{ KDESTROY Command
\par }\pard\plain \s16\li120\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {
\par }\pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {(from UNIX man page)
\par User Commands                                         KDESTROY(1)
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {NAME
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {     kdestroy - destroy Kerberos tickets
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {SYNOPSIS
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {     kdestroy [-q] [-c cache_name]
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {DESCRIPTION
\par      The kdestroy utility destroys  the  user's  active  Kerberos
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {     authorization  tickets  by  writing  zeros  to the specified
\par      credentials cache that contains them.   If  the  credentials
\par      cache  is  not  specified,  the default credentials cache is
\par      destroyed.
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {OPTIONS
\par }\pard\plain \s17\widctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\f0\cgrid      -q   Run quietly.  Normally kdestroy beeps if  it  fails  to
\par }\pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {          destroy  the  user's  tickets.   The -q flag suppresses
\par           this behavior.
\par 
\par      -c cache_name
\par           use cache_name as the credentials (ticket)  cache  name
\par           and  location;  if this option is not used, the default
\par           cache name and location are used.
\par 
\par           The default credentials cache may vary between systems.
\par           If  the  KRB5CCNAME  environment  variable  is set, its
\par           value is used to name the default ticket cache.
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {     Most installations recommend that  you  place  the  kdestroy
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {     command  in your .logout file, so that your tickets are des-
\par      troyed automatically when you log out.
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {ENVIRONMENT
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {     Kdestroy uses the following environment variable:
\par 
\par      KRB5CCNAME      Location of the credentials (ticket) cache.
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {FILES
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {     /tmp/krb5cc_[uid]  default credentials cache ([uid]  is  the
\par                         decimal UID of the user).
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {SEE ALSO
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {kinit(1), klist(1)
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {BUGS
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {     Only the tickets in the specified credentials cache are des-
\par      troyed.   Separate  ticket  caches  are  used  to  hold root
\par      instance and password changing tickets.  These should  prob-
\par      ably  be destroyed too, or all of a user's tickets kept in a
\par      single credentials cache.
\par }\pard\plain \s1\li120\sb280\sa120\sl-320\slmult0\nowidctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright \b\f5 {\page }{\cs15\super ${\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s18\li120\sb80\sl-240\slmult0\nowidctlpar\adjustright \f5\fs20 {\cs15\super $}{
