\par }\pard\plain \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright \fs20\cgrid {To resynchronize your computer's clock to the network's clock, enter the command }{\b gettime -s}{.
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {\b Why Do It...}{
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {Kerberos authentication uses time stamps as part of its protocol. When the clocks of the Kerberos server and your computer are too far out of synchronization, you cannot authenticate properly.
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {\b How To Synchronize Permanently...}{
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {If you always want your computer's clock set to the network time, add the command }{\b gettime -s}{ to the end of your lanwp.bat file.
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {\b How To Query Another Server's Time...}{
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {Use the name of the other machine as a command line option. For example "gettime kerberos.mit.edu" displays the time 
from the computer kerberos.mit.edu. Also "gettime -s kerberos.mit.edu" sets the PC's clock to match the clock on kerberos.mit.edu.
\par 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {\b How It Works}{
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {With no arguments, }{\b gettime}{ contacts the machine "time" and return its time; }{\b gettime -s}{ contacts "time" and resets the clock on your machine to be the same value.
\par The default machine queried by gettime is "time". Currently this is a cname for kerberos.mit.edu if your default domain is mit.edu. If you are not in the mit domain, contact your network administrator and 
ask which machine should be used to resolve time queries.
\par Other sites may wish to set up a machine with the name "time" to simplify this.
