\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {\b TestTracker: What Is It?
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {DCNS uses TestTracker to better determine how thoroughly an application has been tested by volunteer users/testers in the MIT community
. TestTracker-enabled applications can register users/testers as a points of contact, and during alpha and beta tests the version server logs the usage of these applications.
\par During testing, DCNS may ask points of contact to perform specific tests or to report their observations of the application's behavior on their individual computers. The active participation of these testers helps DCNS to create more robust applications.

\par DCNS treats the usage information recorded in the server logs as confidential; the log is available to selected DCNS staff only. 
\par }\pard \widctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright {\b How Does TestTracker Work?
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {Much like the Version Checking capability, the TestTracker makes use of the machine "versions," as described above. When a user first starts a TestTracker-enabled application, it pr
ompts for the user's name and contact information. The user has a number of options for registering:
\par }\pard \fi-600\li720\widctlpar\adjustright {*\tab }{\b Anonymously}{: no name or point contact logged; the TestTracker database still logs the usage of the application.
\par *\tab }{\b Full contact information.}{
\par *\tab }{\b Register this information for all applications}{
: selected information is written to the win.ini file. When started, the current application uses the information for the point of contact, and new TestTracker-enabled applications, when first started, will not prompt the user for this information.
\par *\tab }{\b Register this information for this application ONLY}{: contact information is written into the ini file for the invoked application (and not into the win.ini file).
\par }\pard \widctlpar\adjustright {
